00:05:49.513 --> 00:05:51.534
<v Maya>Every interaction is rigidly planned.</v>

48
00:05:51.614 --> 00:05:52.615
<v Daniel>That's a great way to put it.</v>

49
00:05:52.635 --> 00:06:03.581
<v Maya>But bringing AI into this framework, it's like dropping an improv actor onto the stage. They understand the general theme of the scene, sure, but they have their own agency. They change the lines on the fly based on the audience's reaction.</v>

50
00:06:03.741 --> 00:06:04.221
<v Daniel>Exactly.</v>

51
00:06:04.241 --> 00:06:13.749
<v Maya>But if AI has this... this algorithmic agency, how do designers even map out a service blueprint when the AI might just decide to go completely off script?</v>

52
00:06:13.949 --> 00:06:26.842
<v Daniel>Well, that's the big shift. The researchers argue that service designers have to completely change their mindset. You know, you can no longer create these rigid, static blueprints. Instead, designers must become orchestrators.</v>

53
00:06:27.398 --> 00:06:30.319
<v Maya>orchestrator so you aren't writing the strict dialogue anymore</v>

54
00:06:30.559 --> 00:06:43.765
<v Daniel>no not at all you are designing the environment you're building machine readable interfaces setting up the data architecture and crucially you're establishing the ethical boundaries for what the ai is actually allowed to improvise</v>

55
00:06:44.005 --> 00:06:50.487
<v Maya>oh i see you're building the sandbox setting the rules of the game and then letting the human and the ai play within those constraints</v>

56
00:06:50.567 --> 00:06:54.169
<v Daniel>exactly you orchestrate the conditions rather than scripting the actions</v>

57
00:06:54.774 --> 00:07:03.562
<v Maya>So that's the underlying theory. Let's look at what actually happens when we take that AI to human quadrant, you know, the front stage improv, and actually test it in the wild.</v>

