<v Maya>Oh, wow. So if those top veterans start getting lazy or fatigued and they just start clicking the AI's good enough suggestions instead of coming up with their own brilliant nuanced responses, don't we eventually run out of fresh human genius?</v>

148
00:18:10.507 --> 00:18:11.887
<v Daniel>That is the exact problem.</v>

149
00:18:11.947 --> 00:18:16.108
<v Maya>How do you train the next generation of AI models if the humans stop innovating?</v>

150
00:18:16.328 --> 00:18:18.529
<v Daniel>The paper explicitly flags this risk.</v>

151
00:18:18.749 --> 00:18:18.909
<v Maya>Yeah.</v>

152
00:18:19.089 --> 00:18:25.431
<v Daniel>If human AI collaboration reduces original contributions from top workers, future AI models will absolutely stagnate.</v>

153
00:18:25.451 --> 00:18:27.512
<v Maya>They'll just be training on their own recycled outputs.</v>

154
00:18:28.112 --> 00:18:43.016
<v Daniel>Exactly. An echo chamber of average performance. It highlights a massive design challenge for the future. We have to figure out how to incentivize our human experts to keep innovating, to keep pushing the boundaries of service, even when they have a machine sitting right there</v>

155
00:18:43.116 --> 00:18:44.897
<v Daniel>offering to do the heavy lifting for them.</v>

156
00:18:45.242 --> 00:18:51.263
<v Maya>We have to design systems that reward original human thought. Otherwise, the AI's knowledge base just freezes in time.</v>

157
00:18:51.524 --> 00:18:51.946
<v Daniel>Exactly.</v>

158
00:18:52.363 --> 00:19:06.588
<v Maya>Let's bring this all together. We started with the idea that AI in the service industry fundamentally breaks the old linear equations of business efficiency. And we've seen exactly why today. AI is no longer a backstage calculator. It is an active</v>

159
00:19:06.728 --> 00:19:15.731
<v Maya>co-pilot. It holds this incredible promise for boosting efficiency, leveling the playing field for novices, and capturing the tacit knowledge of an entire workforce.</v>

160
00:19:15.851 --> 00:19:30.707
<v Daniel>Yet the human element still introduces chaos into the system. Our deep-seated psychological bias against talking to machines, that algorithm aversion we talked about, means that front-stage AI faces massive consumer rejection if we don't orchestrate the</v>

161
00:19:30.747 --> 00:19:31.748
<v Daniel>disclosure properly.</v>

162
00:19:32.068 --> 00:19:42.014
<v Maya>Right. And backstage AI, while it's a total miracle for novices, risks distracting our experts and potentially stagnating the very source of the AI's intelligence.</v>

163
00:19:42.235 --> 00:19:44.937
<v Daniel>it really requires a completely new kind of service blueprint.</v>

164
00:19:45.077 --> 00:19:45.978
<v Maya>It absolutely does.</v>

165
00:19:46.038 --> 00:20:00.909
<v Daniel>And looking forward, it leaves us with a pretty provocative thought to mull over. We've seen that generative AI allows someone on their very first day of work to perfectly mimic the empathy, the tone, and the technical knowledge of a 10-year veteran. Yeah. So if that</v>

166
00:20:00.949 --> 00:20:15.864
<v Daniel>becomes the norm, what happens to the inherent value of human expertise? If every single service interaction you have, whether it's negotiating a loan or getting complex technical support, is perfectly optimized and smoothed out by an algorithm, does perfect just become the new</v>

167
00:20:16.205 --> 00:20:22.232
<v Daniel>invisible baseline? Wow. And if perfection is the baseline, how will we as humans ever stand out again?</v>

168
00:20:22.642 --> 00:20:37.365
<v Maya>If everyone has an expert co-pilot, nobody is an expert. Thank you so much for joining us on this deep dive. Next time you call customer service, use a fitness app, or book a hotel, look a little closer at the interaction. Because as we've learned today, there is a</v>

169
00:20:37.405 --> 00:20:43.735
<v Maya>very good chance an algorithm is already acting as the co-pilot, quietly changing the script on the fly. We'll catch you on the next one.</v>
